ay.</TEXT><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Britain's financial markets were buffeted by thepolitical storm over the abrupt resignation of Prime MinisterMargaret Thatcher's treasury secretary.   The markets were jolted Friday by uncertainty over thegovernment's exchange-rate policy and were highly nervous that aresulting steep decline in the British pound would prompt thegovernment to push up interest rates above their 8-year high of 15percent.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   LIN Broadcasting Corp. and BellSouth Corp. haveagreed on a revised plan to merge their cellular telephoneinterests in a deal that would create the nation's largest cellularoperation.   The deal announced Friday, which will be presented to LINshareholders for a vote in December or January, could promptrevision of a pending buyout bid for LIN from McCaw CellularCommunications Inc., the current leader in the cellular field.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   RJR Nabisco Inc. is selling its Baby Ruth,Butterfinger and Pearson candy businesses to Nestle Foods Corp. for$370 million.   The sale, announced Friday, leaves RJR Nabisco about $230million from its goal of $5.5 billion in asset sales for raisingcash to reduce the company's debt load following its $24.53 billionleveraged buyout by Kohlberg Kravis Roberts andamp; Co.   The deal with Nestle, a division of Switzerland's giant NestleSA, includes a manufacturing plant in Franklin Park, Ill.</TEXT><DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A joyful Costa Rican President OscarArias thanked President Bush for the U.S. role in restructuringCosta Rica's foreign debt in ways expected to save his country $100million a year.   Arias announced the debt restructuring Friday at an airportwelcoming ceremony for Bush, who arrived for a meeting withhemispheric leaders.   Arias said the agreement would reduce Costa Rica's $4.5 billionforeign debt by $1 billion. The annual cost of paying interest onthe debt will be reduced from $150 million to $50 million.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The manufacturer of an inhaler for asthmaticsis recalling the medication after just one month on the marketbecause of reports of coughing, choking and gagging after use, theFood and Drug Administration said.   The drug is a new formula of a commonly prescribed metered doseinhaler _ alupent.   The FDA said Friday the medication is being removed from theU.S. market because there has been a sharp increase in reports ofadverse reactions with the reformulation.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Exxon Corp. has resigned from the NationalWildlife Federation's corporate advisory board, calling theconservation group unfair in its criticism of the Alaska oil spill.The unrepentant federation responded by calling Exxon ``a corporatepariah.''   The federation, with 5.8 million members nationwide, accusedExxon on Friday of repeatedly ignoring requests to meet and discussthe spill from the tanker Exxon Valdez.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   The stock market capped off a week-long run of losses withanother broad decline amid worries over weakness in corporateearnings. The Dow Jones industrial average fell 17.01 to 2,596.72Friday, extending its loss for the week to 92.42 points.   The dollar weakened substantially against all major currenciesexcept the British pound.   Bond prices sagged.   Gold futures prices surged to their highest levels in 3{ months;silver and platinum futures rose sharply; copper advanced; oilprices rose; livestock and meat were mostly lower; and grains andsoybeans were mixed.</TEXT></DOC>